    <h2>How to Read Aurora Forecasts Correctly</h2>
    <p>
      Most people misinterpret aurora forecasts. Here's how to read them properly:
    </p>

    <h3>Step 1: Check Current Kp (Nowcast)</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Don't look at 3-day forecast first.</strong> Check the <em>current</em> Kp (updated every 3 hours). If current Kp is high and conditions are good <strong>right now</strong>, go outside immediately.
    </p>

    <h3>Step 2: Verify Your Location's Threshold</h3>
    <p>
      Generic Kp forecasts say "Kp 5 storm tonight" but don't tell you if that's enough for <em>your</em> location. Use this quick reference:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Your Magnetic Latitude</th>
          <th>Required Kp</th>
          <th>Example Cities</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>60¬∞+</td>
          <td>Kp 2-3</td>
          <td>Lerwick, Kirkwall</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>58-60¬∞</td>
          <td>Kp 3-4</td>
          <td>Inverness, Aberdeen</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>56-58¬∞</td>
